  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors (ACEIs) and angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) are particularly effective in patients with diabetes mellitus or chronic kidney disease. Compelling indications for specific classes of antihypertensive agents are based on clinical trial evidence of protection against target organ damage or risk for cardiovascular events. ACEIs and ARBs have been shown to prevent or reverse microalbuminuria and delay the progression of diabetic nephropathy. In the Heart Outcomes Prevention Evaluation (HOPE) study, compared with placebo, treatment with the ACEI ramipril significantly reduced the risk of myocardial infarction, stroke, and cardiovascular mortality in high-risk patients, including diabetics and those with established vascular disease. The benefits were greater than could be attributed to differences in blood pressure control alone. In the Losartan Intervention for Endpoint Reduction in Hypertension (LIFE) study, treatment with the ARB losartan was associated with a greater reduction in cardiovascular morbidity and mortality than was treatment with the beta-blocker atenolol, for similar levels of blood pressure control. ACEIs and ARBs also have favorable effects on left ventricular hypertrophy and ventricular remodeling following myocardial infarction. These agents may be associated with acute renal failure in patients with bilateral renal artery stenosis and hyperkalemia in patients with chronic kidney disease or those taking potassium supplements or potassium-sparing diuretics.",
